Regression Battleship - Creating your Data

Hans Capener

library(pander)
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)

Instructions

Using Desmos, design a “true linear regression model” that is 2D-Drawable, and follows all other Regression Battleship Rules (listed below), that is of the form

\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \underbrace{\quad\quad\quad\ldots\quad\quad\quad}_\text{Your Model Goes Here} + \epsilon_i \quad \text{where} \ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \]

Then, use a simulation in R and your linear regression model to obtain a sample of data saved as rbdata.csv.

Your sample of data will be given to other students and your teacher, but this Rmd file (which contains the secret on how you made your data) will remain hidden until after the competition is complete. Your teacher and two of your peers will use the sample of data your provide, rbdata.csv, to try to guess the true linear regression model you used to create the data. The goal is to hide your model well enough that no one can find it, while keeping the R-squared of your data as high as possible.

Official Rules

Advanced Level Competition

Competing in the Advanced Level will allow you the opportunity to earn full credit on the Regression Battleship portion of your grade in Math 425 (which is 15% of your Final Grade). However, if you compete at this level, you cannot ever discuss your actual model with your teacher. You can still ask for help from the TA, tutors, or other students that you are not competing against. And you can ask “vague” questions to your teacher as long as it doesn’t give too much away about your model.

There are five official rules your model must abide by. If you break any of the rules, you will be disqualified from winning the competition and a grade penalty will result.

  1. Your csv file rbdata.csv must contain 11 columns of data.
    • The first column must be your (1) y-variable (labeled as y).
    • The other ten columns must be (10) x-variables (labeled as x1, x2, … , x10). Please use all lower-case letters. It does not matter which x-variables you use in your model, and you don’t need to use all 10 x-variables in your model.


  1. Your y-variable (or some transformation of the y-variable) must have been created from a linear regression model using only x-variables (or transformations of those x-variables) from within your data set.
    • Be very careful with transformations. You must ensure that you do not break the rules of a linear regression if you choose to use transformations.
    • If you choose transformations, only these functions are allowed when transforming X and Y variables: 1/Y^2, 1/Y, log(Y), sqrt(Y), sqrt(sqrt(Y)), Y^2, Y^3, 1/X^2, 1/X, log(X), sqrt(X), sqrt(sqrt(X)), X^2, X^3, X^4, and X^5. Don’t forget to check Rule #3 carefully if you choose transformations.


  1. Your sample size must be sufficiently large so that when the true model is fit to your data using lm(…), all p-values of terms found in the summary(...) output are significant at the \(\alpha = 0.05\) level.

  2. The \(R^2\) value (“Multiple R-squared”, not the “Adjusted R-squared”) of your true model fit on your rbdata sample must be greater than or equal to \(0.30\). The higher your \(R^2\) value, the more impressive your model.

  3. Your true model must be 2D-drawable. This means that it can be drawn in both Desmos and with a single 2D scatterplot in R.



Intermediate Level Competition

Competing in the Intermediate Level will only allow you to earn up to 88% of the full credit that is possible on the Regression Battleship portion of your grade in Math 425 (which is 15% of your Final Grade). However, getting 88% of the grade is better than failing the advanced level competition and getting 0% of the Regression Battleship grade. So choose this option if you are not feeling comfortable with your abilities to compete at the Advanced Level. The good news is that if you choose this option, your teacher can help you with your model to make sure everything is correct before you turn it in.

For the Intermediate Level competition, there are also five official rules your model must abide by. If you break any of the rules, you will be disqualified from winning the Intermediate Level competition and a point penalty will be applied to your grade.

  1. Your csv file rbdata.csv must contain 6 columns of data.
    • The first column must be your (1) y-variable (labeled as y).
    • The other five columns must be (5) x-variables (labeled as x1, x2, x3, x4 , x5). Please use all lower-case letters. It does not matter which x-variables you use in your model, and you don’t need to use all 5 x-variables in your model.


  1. Your y-variable must have been created from a linear regression model using only x-variables from within your data set.
    • No transformations of y-variables or x-variables are allowed in the Intermediate Level competition.


  1. Your sample size must be sufficiently large so that when the true model is fit to your data using lm(…), all p-values of terms found in the summary(...) output are significant at the \(\alpha = 0.05\) level.

  2. The \(R^2\) value (“Multiple R-squared”, not the “Adjusted R-squared”) of your true model fit on your rbdata sample must be greater than or equal to \(0.80\).

  3. Your true model must be 2D-drawable. This means that it can be drawn in Desmos and with a single 2D scatterplot in R.



Desmos

Start by creating a picture of your true model in Desmos. Snip a screenshot of your completed model. Include a picture of your Desmos graph showing your true model.

Data Creation:

dat = read_excel("BattleshipDat.xlsx") |> 
  select(x1, x2, x3, label)


set.seed(122)
factored <- dat |> 
  mutate(
    label = as.factor(label),
    green = ifelse(label %in% c("x5sqig",
                                "x5sqig7",
                                "x5sqig0.4",
                                "x5sqig0.5",
                                "x5sqig2"),1,0),
    blue = ifelse(label %in% c("1line1",
                               "1line1.45",
                               "1line0.9",
                               "1line2",
                               "1line2.5"),1,0),
    purple = ifelse(label %in% c("x3sqig1",
                                 "x3sqig0.5",
                                 "x3sqig2",
                                 "x3sqig3"),1,0),
    orange = ifelse(label %in% c("2line1:1",
                                 "2line-1:1.34",
                                 "2line-1:0.5",
                                 "2line-0.4:0.8",
                                 "2line-0.5:1.25",
                                 "2line1.6:-0.2",
                                 "2line2.9:0.18",
                                 "2line1.2:0.4"),1,0),
    red = ifelse(label %in% c("2x5sqig1",
                              "2x5sqig6",
                              "2x5sqig2.5",
                              "2x5sqig4",
                              "2x5sqig80",
                              "2x5sqig0.014",
                              "2x5sqig0.018",
                              "2x5sqig0.0087",
                              "2x5sqig0.0067",
                              "2x5sqig0.0022"),1,0),
    black = ifelse(label %in% c("3line1",
                                "3line1.3",
                                "3line1.47",
                                "3line1.54",
                                "3line1.65",
                                "3line1.8",
                                "3line1.7",
                                "3line1.9",
                                "3line2.35",
                                "3line2.32"),1,0),
    x3 = if_else(is.na(x3), sample(c(1.00, 1.34, 0.50, 0.80, 1.25, -0.20),
                           nrow(dat),
                           replace=T), x3)
  )

beta0int = 0.1782962 # Main model intercept
#GREEN
beta0 = -2.52  #intercept
beta1 = 31.56  #x
beta2 = -69.33 #x^{2}
beta3 = 59.49  #x^{3}
beta4 = -22.2  #x^{4}
beta5 = 3      #x^{5}

#BLUE
beta6 = 1

#PURPLE
beta7 = 0.1

#ORANGE
beta8 = 1 #intercept
beta9 = 0.5   #slope

#RED
beta10 = 1.5
beta11 = -3
beta12 = 1.5

#BLACK
beta13 = 1
beta14 = -0.2

calcy <- factored |> 
  mutate(
    y = beta0int +
          green*(beta5*x1^5 +
                   beta4*x1^4 +
                   beta3*x1^3 +
                   beta2*x1^2 +
                   beta1*x1 + 
                   beta0)*x2 +
          blue*(beta6*x1)*x2 +
          purple*(beta7*x1^3)*x2 +
          orange*(beta8*x3 + beta9*x1*x2) +
          red*(beta12*x1^5 +
                   beta11*x1^4 +
                   beta10*x1^3)*x2 +
          black*(beta13*x2+beta14*x1)
                 
  )


## HIDE THE DATA

# Create 3 main columns which, when added, equal mainX, when multiplied, equal the main interaction column
hidden <- calcy |> 
  mutate(
    main1 = (runif(n = nrow(calcy)) - 1)*3,
    main2 = ((x1-main1) + sqrt( (x1-main1)^2 - 4*(x2/main1) ))/2,
    main3 = x1 - main1 - main2,
    mainadd = main1 + main2 + main3,
    mainmult = main1 * main2* main3
  )

for (i in 1:nrow(hidden)) {
  while (is.na(hidden[i, "main2"])) {
    hidden[i,"main1"] <- (runif(1)-1)*3
    hidden[i,"main2"] <- ((hidden[i,"x1"]-hidden[i,"main1"]) + sqrt( (hidden[i,"x1"]-hidden[i,"main1"])^2 - 4*(hidden[i,"x2"]/hidden[i,"main1"]) ))/2
  }
}

hidden <- hidden |> 
  mutate(
    main3 = x1 - main1 - main2,
    mainadd = main1 + main2 + main3,
    mainmult = main1 * main2* main3
  )
hidden$main3 <- as.numeric(format(hidden$main3, scientific=F))

# Create 6 columns that sum to be the switch for the 6 types


for (i in 1:nrow(hidden)) {
  original_vector <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
  remaining_values <- original_vector
  for (j in 1:4) {
    sampled_value <- sample(remaining_values, 1)
    hidden[i, paste0("s", j)] <- sampled_value
    remaining_values <- remaining_values[remaining_values != sampled_value]
  }
  hidden[i, "s5"] <- remaining_values
  
  if (hidden[i, "green"] == 1) {
     hidden[i,"s1"] <- 0
     hidden[i,"s2"] <- 0
     hidden[i,"s3"] <- 0
     hidden[i,"s4"] <- 0
     hidden[i,"s5"] <- 0
    
  } else if (hidden[i, "blue"] == 1) {
        values <- c(1)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s1"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s2"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s3"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s4"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s5"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 0)
    
  } else if (hidden[i, "orange"] == 1) {
        values <- c(1, 2)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s1"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s2"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s3"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s4"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s5"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 0)
    
  } else if (hidden[i, "purple"] == 1) {
        values <- c(1, 2, 3)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s1"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s2"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s3"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s4"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s5"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 0)
    
  } else if (hidden[i, "red"] == 1) {
        values <- c(1, 2, 3, 4)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s1"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s2"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s3"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s4"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s5"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 0)
    
  } else if (hidden[i, "black"] == 1) {
        values <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s1"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s1"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s2"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s2"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s3"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s3"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s4"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s4"] <- 0)
    ifelse(hidden[i, "s5"] %in% values,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 1,
           hidden[i,"s5"] <- 0)

  }
}

Pulling the Truth from the Data:

df <- final |> 
  mutate(
    switches = x2 + x4 + x5 + x9 + x10,
    mainX = x1 + x6 + x8,
    lineInt = x1 * x6 * x8,
    green = ifelse(switches == 0, 1, 0),
    blue = ifelse(switches == 1, 1, 0),
    orange = ifelse(switches == 2, 1, 0),
    purple = ifelse(switches == 3, 1, 0),
    red = ifelse(switches == 4, 1, 0),
    black = ifelse(switches == 5, 1, 0),
  )

mylm <- lm(y~green:I(mainX^5):lineInt + green:I(mainX^4):lineInt
          + green:I(mainX^3):lineInt + green:I(mainX^2):lineInt
          + green:I(mainX):lineInt + green:lineInt +
          blue:mainX:lineInt +
          purple:I(mainX^3):lineInt +
          orange:I(x7) + orange:mainX:lineInt +
          red:I(mainX^5):lineInt + red:I(mainX^4):lineInt + red:I(mainX^3):lineInt +
          black:lineInt+black:mainX, data=df)

Write out your “true” model in mathematical form. Make sure it matches your code. This could be “painful” if you chose a complicated model.

\[ Y_i = 0.1782962 + 3(\text{green}*\text{mainX}^5*\text{lineInt}) + \\ -22.2(\text{green}*\text{mainX}^4*\text{lineInt})\\ + 59.49(\text{green}*\text{mainX}^3*\text{lineInt}) +\\ -69.33(\text{green}*\text{mainX}^2*\text{lineInt})\\ + 31.56(\text{green}*\text{mainX}*\text{lineInt}) +\\ -2.52(\text{green}*\text{lineInt}) +\\ 1(\text{blue}*\text{mainX}*\text{lineInt}) +\\ 0.1(\text{purple}*\text{mainX}^3*\text{lineInt}) +\\ 1(\text{orange}*x7) + 0.5(\text{orange}*\text{mainX}*\text{lineInt}) +\\ 1.5(\text{red}*\text{mainX}^5*\text{lineInt}) +\\ -3(\text{red}*\text{mainX}^4*\text{lineInt}) +\\ 1.5(\text{red}*\text{mainX}^3*\text{lineInt}) +\\ 1(\text{black}*\text{lineInt}) + 0.2(\text{black}*\text{mainX}) \]

Finding the Hidden the Model

Here I will walk through step by step how one would get to my true model, starting from the dataset I gave them.

Lets begin by looking at the dataset, and graphing a pairs plot:

pairs(final, panel=panel.smooth)

Notice we don’t even see the “THX BS!” text from the model; finding that text requires some work.

Normally at this point you would try coloring by different categorical variables to see if there are any trends in the data, but to progress here, we need to mutate some new columns.

First, we add together the three truly quantitative columns (note this does not include x3 or x7, as one of those is text, and the other is categorical). Now, lets graph this new x column against y.

df<-final |> 
  mutate(
    x=x1+x6+x8,
  )
ggplot(df,aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_point()

Now, to find how this text was written with lines. I used 6 different switches to activate different sets of lines to create this model. Finding those switches requires two more column mutations. First, we add together all the “1, 0” switch columns, which gives us a new column with values between 0 and 5. Each of these values is a switch. Lets graph it:

df<-final |> 
  mutate(
    x=x1+x6+x8,
    switches=x2+x4+x5+x9+x10
  )

ggplot(df,aes(x=x,y=y))+
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(
    ~switches
  )

Some may be hard to see how they are made by the same function, but we can see that switch 5 was made with staggered parallel lines. To see what points belong to each line, we need our last mutated column, which comes by multiplying the same 3 lines that we added together to create the main x value with the “THX BS!” text.

df<-final |> 
  mutate(
    x=x1+x6+x8,
    switches=x2+x4+x5+x9+x10,
    mult=x1*x6*x8
  )

ggplot(df,aes(x=x,y=y))+
  geom_point(aes(color=as.factor(mult)),show.legend = F)+
  facet_wrap(
    ~switches
  )

So each switch turns on a base function, and a few multiples of that function; that is why we see lines with the same slope in switch 5, while the intercept is being scaled by our new “multiplier” column. In the end, after playing around with what functions correspond to each switch, you could find out the following:

  • switch 0 is a quintic function, where all terms of the quintic function are scaled to make the new lines.
  • switch 1 is a y=mx line, where x is scaled to make the new lines
  • switch 2 is a y=mx + b line, where x is scaled by the multiplier column, and b (the intecept) is scaled by x7, thus giving us multiple lines with varing slopes and intercecpts
  • switch 3 is a cubic function, again being scaled by the multiplier column.
  • switch 4 was another quintic, also scaled by the multiplier column.
  • switch 5 was a y=x + b, where b was scaled by the multiplier column.

See “R Plot” to see these lines graphed and color coded.

ggplot(df,aes(x=x,y=y))+
  geom_point(aes(color=as.factor(switches)))

  mutate(
    x1=x1+0.2,
    y = beta0int +
          green*(beta5*x1^5 +
                   beta4*x1^4 +
                   beta3*x1^3 +
                   beta2*x1^2 +
                   beta1*x1 + 
                   beta0)*x2 +
          blue*(beta6*x1)*x2 +
          purple*(beta7*x1^3)*x2 +
          orange*(beta8*x3 + beta9*x1*x2) +
          red*(beta12*x1^5 +
                   beta11*x1^4 +
                   beta10*x1^3)*x2 +
          black*(beta13*x2+beta14*x1),
  )


## HIDE THE DATA

# Create 3 main columns which, when added, equal mainX, when multiplied, equal the main interaction column
hidden <- calcy |> 
  mutate(
    main1 = (runif(n = nrow(calcy)) - 1)*3,
    main2 = ((x1-main1) + sqrt( (x1-main1)^2 - 4*(x2/main1) ))/2,
    main3 = x1 - main1 - main2,
    mainadd = main1 + main2 + main3,
    mainmult = main1 * main2* main3
  )

for (i in 1:nrow(hidden)) {
  while (is.na(hidden[i, "main2"])) {
    hidden[i,"main1"] <- (runif(1)-1)*3
    hidden[i,"main2"] <- ((hidden[i,"x1"]-hidden[i,"main1"]) + sqrt( (hidden[i,"x1"]-hidden[i,"main1"])^2 - 4*(hidden[i,"x2"]/hidden[i,"main1"]) ))/2
  }
}

Final Results

The winner is…..BROTHER SAUNDERS.

This decision was very tough, as Preston had the best r-squared and adjusted r-squared for the original data, Tyler had the best r-squared for the validation, and Brother Saunders had the best adjusted r-squared for the validation. After much pondering, I decided that the most important metric was the adjusted r-squared.

yh <- predict(mylm, newdata=hfinal2)
yhp <- predict(holy, newdata=pfinal2)
yht <- predict(lm23, newdata=tfinal2)
yhs <- predict(slm, newdata=final2)

ybar <- mean(final2$y)

SSTO <- sum( (final2$y - ybar)^2 )

# Compute SSE for each model using y - yhat
SSE <- sum( (final2$y - yh)^2 )
SSEt <- sum( (final2$y - yht)^2 )
SSEp <- sum( (final2$y - yhp)^2 )
SSEs <- sum( (final2$y - yhs)^2 )

# Compute R-squared for each
rs <- 1 - SSE/SSTO
rst <- 1 - SSEt/SSTO
rsp <- 1 - SSEp/SSTO
rss <- 1 - SSEs/SSTO


n <- length(final2$y) #sample siz
p <- length(coef(mylm))
pt <- length(coef(lm23)) #num. parameters in model
pp <- length(coef(holy)) #num. parameters in model
ps <- length(coef(slm)) #num. parameters in model
rsa <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-p)*SSE/SSTO
rsta <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-pt)*SSEt/SSTO
rspa <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-pp)*SSEp/SSTO
rssa <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-ps)*SSEs/SSTO

my_output_table2 <- data.frame(Model = c("True", "Tyler", "Preston", "Brother Saunders"), `Original R2` = c(summary(mylm)$r.squared, summary(lm23)$r.squared, summary(holy)$r.squared, summary(slm)$r.squared), `Orig.
